<P>SCENE&mdash;<HI>The Metropolis of the Ma&s;&s;achu&s;etts.</HI></P>
</DIV1>
</FRONT>
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="play">
<PB N="3" REF="019234_0003_0FAA6799AEAB24C0">
<HEAD><HI>SANS SOUCI,</HI> &amp;c.</HEAD>
<DIV2 N="1" TYPE="act">
<HEAD>ACT I.</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE I.</HEAD>
<STAGE>The HALL.</STAGE>
<STAGE>YOUNG FORWARD, and LITTLE PERT.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>YOUNG FORWARD.</SPEAKER>
<P>SANS SOUCI&mdash;free and ea&s;y! This is high bon ton&mdash;Ante-revolution days&mdash;routs&mdash;drums, <HI>&amp;c.</HI> This would do for my Lord <HI>Paxton,</HI>* that e&s;&s;ence of Che&s;terfield: We want &s;ome of that <HI>Sans Souci</HI>
air and addre&s;s, which were &s;o con&s;picuous in that great character; but however we practice very well in the &s;chool of politene&s;s, and a few years will produce many a BEAU NASH in our modern cir|cles.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="4" REF="019234_0004_0FAA679A697791F0">
<SPEAKER>LITTLE PERT.</SPEAKER>
<P>D&mdash;n the old mu&s;ty rules of decency and deco|rum&mdash;national characters&mdash;Spartan virtues&mdash;repub|lican principles&mdash;they are all calculated for rigid manners, and Cromwelian days;&mdash;they are as di&s;|gu<GAP DESC="illegible" REASON="indecipherable" EXTENT="1 letter">&s;ting as old orthodoxy:&mdash;Fa&s;hion and etiquette are more agreeable to my ideas of life&mdash;this is the independence I aim at&mdash;the free and ea&s;y air which &s;o di&s;tingui&s;hes the man of fa&s;hion, from the &s;elf-formal republican&mdash;the court &s;tile&mdash;the <HI>j&ecirc; ne &s;cai quoi</HI>&mdash;give me but this and away with all your buckram of Pre&s;beteriani&s;m.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>YOUNG FORWARD.</SPEAKER>
<P>I find, my good friend, you have a genuine idea of ta&s;te.&mdash;From the many &s;tarched &s;enti|ments which &s;ome of our Old Dons have endeavour|ed to in&s;til among us by their re&s;olves&mdash;town-meet|ings, <HI>&amp;c.</HI> I expected we &s;hould all, at the clo&s;e of the war, be obliged to be confined to our clo&s;ets to learn political creeds and read political di&s;qui&s;iti|ons&mdash;and in&s;tead of balls, concerts and card-parties, we &s;hould be employed in writing di&s;&s;ertations on government:&mdash;Happy rever&s;e! We have now worn off tho&s;e old fa&s;hion &s;entiments, and can breathe the free air of gallantry and etiquette.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LITTLE PERT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Can any pro&s;pect be more plea&s;ing than the brilliant appearance of this Hall?&mdash;What a fine arrangement!&mdash;Let me &s;ee&mdash;twenty card-tables. &mdash;Behold tho&s;e agreeable ladies!&mdash;what animated countenances!&mdash;How the chance of play gives new
<PB N="5" REF="019234_0005_0FAA679B30C590B0">
vivacity to their eyes!&mdash;How charming this a&s;&s;em|blage of flowers in this garden of beauty!&mdash;What a beautiful variety adorns this parterre!&mdash;This is an improvement of Eden, there only <HI>one fruit</HI> tempted our fir&s;t parents, but here they hang in &s;uch clu&s;ters, that we are &s;urrounded in the circle of temptations.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>YOUNG FORWARD.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not only the ladies, but I think the gentle|men appear with a particular grace.&mdash;We have the happy faculty of blending bu&s;ine&s;s and amu&s;e|ments&mdash;I hate tho&s;e <HI>tare</HI> and <HI>tret</HI> fellows in London, that can only make a figure in a <HI>compting hou&s;e,</HI> and walk a-thrawt a room as clum&s;y as <HI>gro&s;s hundreds,</HI> meer <HI>avoirdupois</HI> weight;&mdash;I like to &s;ee a man throw a&s;ide his profe&s;&s;ional character, and enter a po|lite circle with the <HI>Sans Souci</HI> air of a petit maitre&mdash; and in&s;tead of plodding in a <HI>Ledger</HI> over <HI>Dr.</HI> and <HI>Cr.</HI> I like to &s;ee him ver&s;ed in all the tender &s;tile of a billet doux&mdash;not calculated &s;olely to <HI>ballance ac|counts,</HI> but to decide with preci&s;&s;ion the arrangements of a lady's toilette.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LITTLE PERT.</SPEAKER>
<P>When I was at New-York, among the Bri|ti&s;h, I was a&s;hamed to acknowledge my&s;elf a Bo&s;tonian&mdash;we had &s;uch a particular character&mdash;we were always pictured as a &s;et of canting pre&s;beterians, who began Sundays before &s;un &s;et on Saturday, and held out praying until Monday morning at &s;unri&s;e&mdash; that all our diver&s;ions were &s;inging p&s;alms, and going to Thur&s;day-Lectures.&mdash;But thank Heaven we can now hold up our heads amid&s;t the mo&s;t po|lite
<PB N="6" REF="019234_0006_0FAA679BE8F4ECA0">
circle at Raneleigh, or join with full eclat the brilliant a&s;&s;embly at Vauxhall.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>YOUNG FORWARD.</SPEAKER>
<P>For the pre&s;ent we will &s;eperate&punc; as our extacies may po&s;&s;ibly be ob&s;erved by the company.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exeunt.</STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE II.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>The</HI> DRAWING-ROOM.</STAGE>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>Madam IMPORTANCE</HI> and <HI>Madam BRILLIANT.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Madam IMPORTANCE.</SPEAKER>
<P>PRAY waiter are there much company this evening?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WAITER.</SPEAKER>
<P>A great deal, Madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Madam BRILLIANT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Are they very brilliant in their dre&s;s?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WAITER.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very much &s;o, Madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Madam BRILLIANT.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am &s;orry the ladies have been &s;o attentive to their dre&s;s, as I am afraid this will occa&s;ion the
<PB N="7" REF="019234_0007_0FAA679CF6967108">
breaking up this entertainment&mdash;as the gentlemen will by and bye make this a plea, after they find it is attended with &s;o great expence.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Madam IMPOTANCE.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't be apprehen&s;ive on this account&mdash;this is the very thing I was in hopes would take place&mdash;this will &s;erve to <HI>&s;i<GAP DESC="illegible" REASON="indecipherable" EXTENT="1 letter">t down families,</HI> and will be the mo&s;t effectual means to e&s;tabli&s;h a <HI>precedency</HI> &mdash;we have for a long while been too much on a level&mdash;once a fortnight a publick a&s;&s;embly, will for a long time, keep up this <HI>equality</HI>&mdash; but the oftner we meet, tho&s;e which cannot keep pace, will be obliged to re&s;ign their preten&s;ions to high life, and leave a few of <HI>us</HI> to enjoy the field&mdash; for my own part, I conceive it to be the happie&s;t plan that could have been adopted&mdash;it en&s;nares peo|ple in their own trap&punc; which you know, Madam, is the mo&s;t effectual method to en&s;ure their de&s;truction.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Madam BRILLIANT.</SPEAKER>
<P>If tho&s;e are your intentions, Madam, we mu&s;t car|ry it much further, and in&s;tead of a few &s;hillings, which I &s;uppo&s;e the generality will play for, we mu&s;t e&s;tabli&s;h at our own table the rubbers of ten guineas at lea&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>Mr. IMPORTANCE</HI> and <HI>Dr. GALLANT.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Doct. GALLANT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ladies, your &s;ervant.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LADIES.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your &s;ervant, gentlemen.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="8" REF="019234_0008_0FAA679F67B2B840" MS="y">
<SPEAKER>Mr. IMPORTANCE.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ladies, &s;hall I be permitted to hand you into the Hall?&mdash;You will be <HI>mon&s;trou&s;ly</HI> plea&s;ed with the appearance.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Madam BRILLIANT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Are all the tables full?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Doct. GALLANT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mo&s;tly madam- but a few are re&s;erved for cer|tain ladies&mdash;not to be taken up by the company, until we know whether cartain characters will be of the company for the evening.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Madam IMPORTANCE.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very right&mdash;I am glad you have thought to make this re&s;erve&mdash;as di&s;tinctions in all companies are ne|ce&s;&s;ary.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exeunt.</STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="3" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE III.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>The</HI> HALL.</STAGE>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>Mr. IMPORTANCE, JEMMY SATIRIST,</HI> and <HI>Doctor GALLANT.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEMMY SATIRIST.</SPEAKER>
<P>WHAT mo&s;t &s;urpri&s;es me, is, that the plan was &s;o readily con&s;ented to&mdash;the parade of the card-table has been &s;o long out of fa&s;hion&mdash;I did
<PB N="9" REF="019234_0009_0FAA67A092BA28B0" MS="y">
not think they would with &s;o much alacrity, have in|troduced it into a publick a&s;&s;embly&mdash;however, we are fond of novelty, and the fa&s;cinating charms of high life have too many allurements to be re&s;i&s;ted.&mdash; We have made a notable caveat&mdash;not to play beyond one &s;hilling and &s;ix pence upon our HONOUR! there's the rub&mdash;Gaming is like a coy mi&s;tre&s;s, who&s;e meer &s;miles we at fir&s;t think a happine&s;s&mdash;but when tho&s;e become familiar, we urge forward to more <HI>&s;ub&s;tantial</HI> joys.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. IMPORTANCE.</SPEAKER>
<P>We have in our <HI>profe&s;&s;ional character,</HI> a mighty influence in carrying any plans we wi&s;h to adopt&mdash; for my own part, I endeavour to inforce every thing with the prerogative of the of the <HI>black robes,</HI> and dre&s;&s;ed in the <HI>&s;able livery,</HI> can e&s;tabli&s;h doctrines of etiquette, with equal deci&s;ion, as our brethren of the pulpit can their articles of faith.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Doct. GALLANT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well it is quite right&mdash;profe&s;&s;ional characters mu&s;t be &s;upported with dignity&mdash;otherways, all di&s;|tinctions will be lo&s;t in the levelling &s;pirit of repub|licani&s;m&mdash;therefore, if we expect to &s;upport ta&s;te and &s;tile, we mu&s;t keep up this parade, and by a&s;|&s;uming an appearance above the commonality, we may &s;tamp on our characters a <HI>&s;uperiority</HI> of rank.&mdash; This may appear a new doctrine&mdash;<HI>that in order to promote di&s;tinction, we mu&s;t introduce all into one &s;ociety</HI>&mdash; but depend upon it, a particular <HI>deportment</HI> ob&s;erved at &s;uch times, more effectually &s;ecures pre|eminence than &s;hutting ones &s;elf up from the crowd.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="10" REF="019234_0010_0FAA67A12EF3A358">
<SPEAKER>Mr. IMPORTANCE.</SPEAKER>
<P>Upon my word, Doctor, you have improved on Che&s;terfield&mdash;I have ever thought that keeping aloof, and only appearing at times, when &s;ome im|portant que&s;tions were agitated, would be mo&s;t likely to &s;ecure my importance&mdash;a town-meeting harangue, (for in&s;tance) I conceived would produce wonderful effects&mdash;and then retiring with a peculiar ea&s;y air of con&s;equence, would &s;ecure the re&s;pectful complai|&s;ance of the whole a&s;&s;embly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEMMY SATIRIST.</SPEAKER>
<P>No per&s;on can di&s;pute with brother <HI>Importance</HI> his right of &s;tation in the beau monde&mdash; he &s;oon threw off all incumbrances, and like a true di&s;ciple, for&s;ook ALL&mdash;he had no notion of mounting the mere <HI>&s;hadow of Pega&s;us,</HI> but cho&s;e rather to prance among the Mu&s;es with the nag fully capari&s;oned&mdash; however brother, not to be too &s;evere&mdash;but we gen|tlemen of the &mdash; &s;ometimes take the liberty to abu&s;e each other, as well as our C&mdash;s&mdash;Indulgen|cies!&mdash;Indulgencies, brother!&mdash;But let us ha&s;ten a|mong the company, as the tables begin to be filled.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exeunt.</STAGE>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="2" TYPE="act">
<PB N="11" REF="019234_0011_0FAA67A213600D70">
<HEAD>ACT II.</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE I.</HEAD>
<STAGE>Enter The REPUBLICAN HEROINE and Mrs. W&mdash;N.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>REPUBLICAN HEROINE.</SPEAKER>
<P>I HAVE been complimented with a Card for a new Entertaiment called Sans Souci.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. W&mdash;N.</SPEAKER>
<P>Have you attended?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>REP. HEROINE.</SPEAKER>
<P>Upon my word, Madam, I was a long while con&s;i|dering whether it was a real or imaginary compliment: I could &s;carcely believe it po&s;&s;ible, that this country, particularly this town, who&s;e name &s;tands foremo&s;t in the annals of America, &s;hould &s;o early plunge into the utmo&s;t exce&s;&s;es of di&s;&s;ipation: How will &s;uch an account read among the friends of America in Europe. I could hardly refrain from tears when I entered the Hall, to &s;ee the re&s;pectable inhabitants of this metropolis, &s;o wantonly introducing a cu&s;tom of publick card playing, even at &s;o early a period after the war. Forgive me, Madam, my expre&s;&s;ing my &s;entiments &s;o freely; but believe me I have hi|therto indulged &s;uch plea&s;ing ideas re&s;pecting this country, from their publick proceedings during the war, that when I find those &s;entiments of their virtue turn out mere chimeras of my own imagina|tion, I cannot but lament my di&s;appointment. The
<PB N="12" REF="019234_0012_0FAA67A2B5308808">
re&s;pect that has been &s;hewn me &s;ince my arrival, I mo&s;t gratefully acknowledge, but often on my re|tiring from the parade of their entertainments. I can|not but pity their delu&s;ion. I did not carry my en|thu&s;ia&s;m &s;o far as to expect to find the rigid Spartan principles practi&s;ed; but I did conceive to be intro|duced into &s;ocieties of frugality and oeconomy: I did expect to find a cultivation of manners &s;ome|what &s;imilar to their publick re&s;olves; but again par|don me, Madam, when I inform you I am greatly di&s;appointed. Briti&s;h gewgaws &mdash;etiquette and pa|rade, are too prevailing to be ea&s;ily eradicated, un|le&s;s &s;ome immediate exertions are made to turn this de&s;tructive current: As a &s;tranger, I cannot with propriety &s;et up to give examples, but on ladies of e&s;tabli&s;hed characters in the country, much ought to be expected from them.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. W&mdash;N.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am very unhappy to find your ob&s;ervations are &s;o ju&s;t. I cannot but acknowledge we have too far copied the vices of that nation which we have &s;o late|ly oppo&s;ed: But however, I do not think this late entertaiment will be long continued; there are many re&s;pectable characters among them, who I am per|&s;uaded when they con&s;ider the dangerous tendency of this a&s;&s;embly, will readily di&s;countenance it. We mu&s;t be convinced how dangerous to the morals of youth&mdash;how de&s;tructive to the happine&s;s of families and individuals, an introduction of card parties has ever been; therefore though they have become of the party, which from inattention, rather than from inclination to promote a &s;pirit of di&s;&s;ipation they at
<PB N="13" REF="019234_0013_0FAA67A36E5E4128">
fir&s;t engaged in it; they will readily give up the entertainment, and even di&s;countenance the promoters of it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>REP. HEROINE,</SPEAKER>
<P>I wi&s;h &s;incerely you may not be di&s;appointed in your hopes; but, my dear Madam,
'Vice is a mon&s;ter of &s;o frightful mein,' <HI>&amp;c.</HI></P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exeunt.</STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE II.</HEAD>
<STAGE>YOUNG FORWARD, and LITTLE PERT.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>YOUNG FORWARD</SPEAKER>
<P>I HAVE been to all the Book&s;ellers in town to purcha&s;e <HI>Hoyle</HI>; but find they have been all bought up.&mdash;There are propo&s;als in the Drawing-Room for a new edition with improvements; al&s;o there is to be kept a minute Book for remarks on the game of whi&s;t, as many particular ca&s;es may take place in the cour&s;e of play which will render it a valuable collection, as an appendix to this new e|dition; the whole are to be revi&s;ed by our D-r-ct&mdash;s, and dedicated to them.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LITTLE PERT&punc;</SPEAKER>
<P>A good propo&s;al! Let me &s;ee the &s;ub&s;cription:&mdash; To promote the work I will &s;ub&s;cribe for 100 books. However, we are &s;o d &mdash;d contracted in this town, we
<PB N="14" REF="019234_0014_0FAA67A44107C758" MS="y">
&s;hall never come to a full improvement in the polite arts.&mdash;The pre&s;ent card party is a mere burle&s;que on the in&s;titution!&mdash;How ridiculous we appear!- A guinea a corner alarms one half of them:&mdash;There are but few tables here that dare hazard&mdash;I almo&s;t &s;car'd one fellow into panicks, and a lady into hy&s;te|ricks, by offering to bet ten guineas on the rubber: They made an&s;wer they did not play &s;o high.&mdash;Was there any thing ever &s;o laughable? What the devil do they come here for? Do they come merely to &s;huffle a pack of cards? We might as well be in a private party;&mdash;let us be &s;omething or nothing:&mdash; <HI>A card party gingling &s;hillings and &s;ix pences</HI>; Ha, ha, ha.&mdash;The circle of etiquette with pur&s;es of &s;il|ver;&mdash;this would &s;ound high at BROOKs;&mdash;A re|publican card party; quite a political phaenomenon. However never mind it, Rome was not built in a day;&mdash;<HI>free and ea&s;y</HI> is our motto, and we are fond of con&s;i&s;tency&mdash;per&s;everando.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>YOUNG FORWARD.</SPEAKER>
<P>We are often bemoaning the want of plays in this town;&mdash;this will be a con&s;iderable introduction to this entertainment; we can with the greate&s;t pro|priety a&s;k permi&s;&s;ion for a theatre after we have been indulged with a card party; for of two evils, plays mu&s;t be con&s;idered the lea&s;t;&mdash;&s;o that we have no|thing to do, but to re&s;ign for a &s;ea&s;on our card a|mu&s;ements until we can get a theatre erected, and af|ter that we can return to our pre&s;ent entertainment by pleading <HI>precedents</HI>; for we mu&s;t hold precedents as tenacious in the polite circle, as we lawyers do <HI>authorities</HI> in our profe&s;&s;ion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="15" REF="019234_0015_0FAA67A4EF2EB470">
<SPEAKER>LITTLE PERT.</SPEAKER>
<P>But one e&s;&s;ential matter I am afraid we &s;hall be deprived of;&mdash;Graham &mdash;the celebrated Doctor Gra|ham;&mdash;the coele&s;tial bed;&mdash;hah!&mdash;here the Cu|pids would ne&s;tle on the downy pillows: Lectures on love;&mdash;the&s;e are Evening Lectures worth attending to: I dare &s;ay he would have a thronged a&s;&s;embly; a full congregation&mdash;zealots&mdash;enthu&s;ia&s;ts&mdash;high or|thodoxy&mdash;this would be a hopeful &s;chool of good breeding&mdash;all well ver&s;ed in the principles of galan|try&mdash;no awkward mode&s;ty, and &s;hame-face'd diffi|dence&mdash;but full confidence&mdash;polite amours;&mdash;never be afraid, we &s;hall &s;oon pave the way for this amu&s;e|ment&mdash;lectures &s;urely cannot be di&s;approved&mdash;who can object to lectures?&mdash;We could blind one half the old women in town, by telling them the cele|brated Doctor Graham intended to deliver evening lectures on various &s;ubjects&mdash;they would at lea&s;t think him a &s;econd Whitfield.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>YOUNG FORWARD.</SPEAKER>
<P>You have a happy faculty at anticipation&mdash;but however let us be going, for while I attend to your rhap&s;ody, I am lo&s;ing the pre&s;ent amu&s;ement.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exeunt.</STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="3" TYPE="scene">
<PB N="16" REF="019234_0016_0FAA67A5AB5809F0">
<HEAD>SCENE III.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>The</HI> DRAWING-ROOM.</STAGE>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>Madam IMPORTANCE</HI> and <HI>Madam BRILLIANT.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Madam IMPORTANCE.</SPEAKER>
<P>WHAT an awkward piece of bu&s;ine&s;s this is! I am really tired.&mdash;The foreign lady<NOTE N="*" PLACE="foot">This is not pointed at any particular foreign character now among us, but what is likely may happen in future.</NOTE> who was at our table, alarmed &s;ome of our circle, by lay|ing down a pur&s;e of ten guineas. As our a&s;&s;embly was &s;omewhat &s;imilar to tho&s;e in England&mdash;&s;he (I &s;uppo&s;e) thought we did in &s;ome degree practice playing, at lea&s;t to the amount of &s;o triffling a &s;um&mdash; we all &s;tared at each other&mdash;for my own part I did not like to tell her we did not play &s;o high, or to inform her of our re&s;olutions to the contrary, as we &s;hould make but an indifferent appearance to her, if we &s;uppo&s;ed &s;uch a &s;um were extravagant&mdash;how|ever, as it was late, I pretended to be fatigued, and threw up my hand, with an apology that I was in|di&s;po&s;ed;&mdash;&s;he even &s;eemed &s;urpri&s;ed at my indi&s;|po&s;ition, and exclaimed&mdash;<HI>indi&s;po&s;ed at a card-table!</HI> I therefore found my complaints were intirely foreign from etiquette&mdash;however, I &s;till peri&s;ted in my in|di&s;po&s;ition, and the lady ob&s;erving my embarra&s;&s;|ment, politely declined urging me any further.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Madam BRILLIANT.</SPEAKER>
<P>This is a circum&s;tance of which I was not aware,
<PB N="17" REF="019234_0017_0FAA67A6AA000788">
as we may in time expect foreigners among us&punc; they will naturally &s;uppo&s;e from &s;o polite a circle, they may <HI>bet</HI> as at a&s;&s;emblies they have frequented in Europe&mdash;and being from our &s;tations, introduced to their tables, we &s;hall often be put to the di&s;agreea|ble nece&s;&s;ity of pleading indi&s;po&s;ition &mdash; and indi&s;po&s;i|tion may in time, become a cant term among the polite circle for declining a bet:&mdash;Free and ea&s;y therefore is not very applicable to our pre&s;ent &s;itua|tion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Madam IMPORTANCE.</SPEAKER>
<P>To morrow we will talk over this affair at our lei&s;ure.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exeunt.</STAGE>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="3" TYPE="act">
<HEAD>ACT III.</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE. I.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>The</HI> HALL.</STAGE>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>Mr. IMPORTANCE JEMMY SATIRIST,</HI> and <HI>Doctor GALLANT.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. IMPORTANCE.</SPEAKER>
<P>HOW we can divert our&s;elves through the &s;everal rooms?&mdash;In one circle we can ob&s;erve the mo&s;t agreeable parties of ladies, &s;eated at the &s;everal tables, which look like an a&s;&s;embly of Godde&s;&s;es! The Graces &s;eem here to have taken up their re&s;i|dence&mdash;&s;uch a beautiful variety di&s;played in the ar|rangement
<PB N="18" REF="019234_0018_0FAA67A72B20F078" MS="y">
of their dre&s;s, adds to the redundancy of their charms: Within this Hall, I would ri&s;que the reputation we have already acquired, of having as fine a collection of ladies in our a&s;&s;embly, as any th world can produce.&mdash;However, &s;ometimes I can &s;ee a little anxiety in a countenance&mdash;it is a pity to ful|ly one lu&s;tre amid &s;uch a clu&s;ter of charms &mdash; but ta&s;te and etiquette mu&s;t be complied with, however fatal the con&s;equences may be to beauty.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEMMY SATIRIST.</SPEAKER>
<P>This is a pretty harangue, brother <HI>Importance,</HI> one would almo&s;t &s;uppo&s;e you was fee'd by the ladies&mdash; but I am &s;en&s;ible you have a good cau&s;e, and may be &s;ure of a verdict in your favour. It is a pity you had not always &s;poke your mind with &s;o much &s;afe|ty, for nothing is more fatal to a man of fa&s;hion than doing any thing reflecting on the ladies&mdash;it was ra|ther unfortunate in your fir&s;t appearing on the pub|lick &s;tage, to have &s;uch a hue and cry after you&mdash; but however, not to call to mind things pa&s;t&mdash;I wi&s;h the ladies had heard this late panegyrick.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Doct. GALLANT.</SPEAKER>
<P>While you are attending to the appearance of their per&s;ons, you do not ob&s;erve the gracefulne&s;s of their dancing&mdash;T&mdash;r has a mo&s;t happy faculty a<GAP DESC="illegible" REASON="indecipherable" EXTENT="1 letter"> teaching&mdash;like a limner, he <HI>draws every grace of gentility, and blends ea&s;e and addre&s;s in every fea|ture</HI>&mdash;however, let us leave this &s;ubject, and talk on &s;ome other.&mdash;Pray have you &s;een Doctor Price's new publication?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="19" REF="019234_0019_0FAA67A98B1933A8" MS="y">
<SPEAKER>Mr. IMPORTANCE.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Doct. GALLANT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, what do you think of it?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr&middot; IMPORTANCE.</SPEAKER>
<P>The Doctor would do to live in Carthage, Sparta, or Rome in the mo&s;t rigid times; but now tho&s;e &s;en|timents are wholly imaginary ideas of a Republican's coran&mdash; they are too antiquated&mdash;modern rebublica|ni&s;m is of a very different complexion, as contra&s;ted as the &s;evere countenance of Cromwell, and the pret|ty &s;mooth face of a petit maitre&mdash;tho&s;e of the Doctor's are principles of republicani&s;m of the un|civilized kind&mdash;but now we &s;often them down in the &s;chool of politene&s;s, and make them wear a more plea&s;ing garb&mdash;the antient rebublican &s;pirit is like the old principles of religion&mdash;&s;taunch Calvini&s;m&mdash; but now we have modernized them, and united them with the court &s;tile of ta&s;te and fa&s;hion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>JEMMY SATIRIST.</SPEAKER>
<P>The Doctor's &s;entiments did well enough in war times, when we were under the influence of whig principles&mdash;this mercury did very well in our politi|cal thermometer&mdash;but now we have no occa&s;ion for this blood heat&mdash;they were plea&s;ing doctrines to preach up at that time, but now, why are we to be ding'd with national manners&mdash;national debts&mdash;oeco|nomy&mdash;indu&s;try and &s;uch di&s;agreeable &s;ubjects?&mdash; Independence in the original is my idea&mdash;high court independence&mdash;independent of every re&s;traint which can mar the plea&s;ures and amu&s;ements of life.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="20" REF="019234_0020_0FAA67AAAB473558">
<SPEAKER>Doct. GALLANT.</SPEAKER>
<P>I know the old Dons lift up their eyes with hor|ror, when they &s;ee what they call the <HI>old principles</HI> &s;ub&s;iding &mdash; they are as tenacious of their <HI>old &s;enti|ments,</HI> as they are of their white wigs&mdash; but we know better&mdash;we act on the <HI>benevolent</HI> plan&mdash;why &s;hould we ever keep up a d&mdash;n di&s;tinction between whig and tory?&mdash;For my own part, I wi&s;h to em|brace <GAP DESC="illegible" REASON="indecipherable" EXTENT="1 letter">LL, and this very a&s;&s;embly is one means of introducing to a <HI>&s;ociability</HI> the &s;everal parties which have been di&s;tinct through the war&mdash;let all political di&s;tinctions be buried, and let us with fraternal affec|tion embrace every one whatever may have been his principles during the war, or however inimical his conduct&mdash;the&s;e are genuine &s;entiments and agree|able to our modern republicani&s;m &mdash; We mu&s;t de&s;i&s;t from our political ob<GAP DESC="illegible" REASON="indecipherable" EXTENT="1 letter">ervations for the pre&s;ent.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exeunt.</STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD>SCENE II.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>The</HI> ENTRY.&mdash;SERVANTS.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cuffy.</SPEAKER>
<P>WAT clok Jack?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jack.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pa&s;s twelbe clok.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cuffy.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dis be no lik ole Ma&s;&s;a tims&mdash;ten clok, go bed&mdash;de gate &s;hot &mdash;go prarrs&mdash;all de &s;erbants go bed&mdash;Ma&s;&s;a put out de fire.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jack.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ye&s;&s;e Cuffe&mdash; but you be ole fello&mdash; I
<PB N="21" REF="019234_0021_0FAA67AAEE941668">
like bery vel dis &s;etin up&mdash;Ma&s;&s;a and Mi&s;&s;e brod&mdash; gate open all nite&mdash;why you fool, what optunty for &s;erbants? But when Ma&s;&s;a and Mi&s;&s;e kep hom all de ebning, go bed ten clok, what time for poor &s;er|bants frolik.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cuffy.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ma&s;&s;a and Me&s;&s;e come home twelbe clok, &s;cold and hangry&mdash;poor &s;erbants pay for all&mdash;find falt wid ebery ting&mdash;noting rite.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jack.</SPEAKER>
<P>You neber been Ningland Cuffe&mdash;dar fin tims&mdash;pre&s;enly Bo&s;&s;on lik it&mdash;ma&s;&s;erades&mdash;pan|tons&mdash;no litle Corn&s;hort-Hal for gentry&mdash; pre&s;enly panton&mdash;tea-trays&mdash;flambeaux&mdash;no dribe wid one poor ho&s;&s;e and &s;ha&mdash; but tree &s;erbants&mdash;no one poor deble lik you&s;elf&mdash;but libry &s;erbants.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cuffy.</SPEAKER>
<P>Me be owl felo Jack&mdash;but I frad too tru&mdash;me here notin now but Sam and Su&s;y&mdash;me dont no wat day meen&mdash;but me here dem &s;ay, we go Sam and Su&s;y to night&mdash;d&mdash;n baboon.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Jack.</SPEAKER>
<P>Baboon&mdash;Cuffe wat you &s;ay?&mdash;Balloon you mean.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cuffy,</SPEAKER>
<P>Hah, balloon&mdash;wel no mater for dat.</P>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="3" TYPE="scene">
<PB N="22" REF="019234_0022_0FAA67ABB3F19B80">
<HEAD>SCENE III.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>The</HI> HALL.&mdash;A Card Table.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Mr. BON TON, Madam IMPORTANCE&punc; Madam BRIL|LIANT,</HI> and <HI>Dr. GALLANT</HI>&punc;</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Madam BRILLIANT.</SPEAKER>
<P>A DIAMOND led, Mr. Bon Ton.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. BON TON.</SPEAKER>
<P>I beg pardon, Madam&mdash;but there is &s;o much laughing, whi&s;pering and talking in the room, that I am quite embarra&s;&s;ed in my play.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Madam IMPORTANCE.</SPEAKER>
<P>I believe, Sir, you have not been u&s;ed to play in a &s;ocial circle&mdash;but rather in places where every idea is ab&s;orb'd in the game.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. BON TON.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why truly, Madam, I have imbibed the manners of Europe &s;o far, that I cannot have ears to attend to conver&s;ation, and eyes to ob&s;erve the variety of objects around me, and at the &s;ame time pay &s;o great attention to the play as to know the di&s;po&s;ition of the cards.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Madam IMPORTANCE.</SPEAKER>
<P>I find, Sir, you practice wholly on the &s;tricte&s;t principles of whi&s;t;&mdash;but we endeavour to make this game only an evening's amu&s;ement.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="23" REF="019234_0023_0FAA67AC6DA30778">
<SPEAKER>Mr. BON TON.</SPEAKER>
<P>Amu&s;ement, Madam, is not the principle in Eu|rope; po&s;&s;ibly the fir&s;t in&s;titutions of this kind were e&s;tabli&s;hed on the&s;e principles and &s;uppo&s;e the &s;ums to be play'd for, were limited, as among us;&mdash;but the company which now vi&s;it tho&s;e places of publick re&s;ort, do not go for amu&s;ement &s;olely, but to pur|&s;ue a regular branch of bu&s;ine&s;s.&mdash;They have no idea of playing to pa&s;s away a few lei&s;ure hours, but to improve the moments for their profit&mdash;they are their bu&s;y hours&mdash;the time on which depends their future pro&s;pects. Therefore no conver&s;ation while at play is admitted, but what is on the &s;ubject of the game, and a per&s;on would appear equally as ridiculous to be &s;peaking at that time on any other &s;ubject, as to be talking of Hoyle at the tabernacle.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Madam BRILLIANT.</SPEAKER>
<P>You have quite forgot your play, by your lengthy ob&s;ervations.&mdash;Hearts are trumps.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. BON TON.</SPEAKER>
<P>And have been &s;o, Madam, ever &s;ince you entered the room.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Madam BRILLIANT.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;uppo&s;e compliments are agreeable to the rules laid down by Hoyle?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. BON TON.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Madam, and are often played to great advan|tage.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="24" REF="019234_0024_0FAA67AD34C52F90">
<SPEAKER>Madam IMPORTANCE.</SPEAKER>
<P>I always &s;u&s;pect a gentleman's hand when he be|gins to compliment the lady he plays again&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. BON TON.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;uppo&s;e, Madam, you conceive it a <HI>fine&s;&s;e</HI>;&mdash;at lea&s;t for the <HI>odd trick.</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Madam BRILLIANT.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;uppo&s;e you calculate by the table of chances?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. BON TON.</SPEAKER>
<P>I do, Madam, but my &s;ucce&s;s depends on your &s;miles.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Doctor GALLANT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pray how are we for game?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. BON TON.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nine.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Madam BRILLIANT.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, Sir, we will for the pre&s;ent be whi&s;t, and endeavour to fini&s;h before 12 o'clock.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. BON TON.</SPEAKER>
<P>The hours pa&s;s mo&s;t rapidly;&mdash;but however, Ma|dam, we mu&s;t not find fault with time, for in your company <HI>eternity</HI> can be the only mea&s;ure of our happine&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Madam BRILLIANT.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hall not an&s;wer you at pre&s;ent, as it is time to withdraw.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exeunt omnes.</STAGE>
